definition: "Selenium is an essential trace mineral incorporated into a family of proteins called selenoproteins — at least 25 of which have been identified in humans. Selenoproteins perform critical functions in antioxidant defense (glutathione peroxidases, which reduce hydrogen peroxide and lipid peroxides), thyroid hormone metabolism (iodothyronine deiodinases, which convert T4 to the active T3), DNA synthesis and repair (thioredoxin reductases), immune function, and reproductive health. Selenium is incorporated into selenoproteins via the amino acid selenocysteine — sometimes called the 21st amino acid — in a ribosomal process that requires adequate selenium intake to proceed."
why_it_matters: "Selenium has a narrower therapeutic window than most nutrients — both deficiency and excess carry meaningful health risks, making it one of the few micronutrients where more is definitively not better. Deficiency impairs the glutathione antioxidant system, reduces thyroid hormone activation, suppresses immune function, and is associated with elevated cancer risk and faster biological aging. Excess selenium (selenosis) causes nail brittleness, hair loss, neurological effects, and in severe cases cardiovascular toxicity. The longevity-optimal range reflects a U-shaped dose-response curve: the benefit accrues from achieving sufficiency, not from maximizing intake. Selenium status varies enormously with geography because soil selenium content determines the selenium in locally grown food — populations in selenium-poor regions (parts of Europe, China, New Zealand) are at substantially higher deficiency risk than those in selenium-rich regions (much of the US and Canada)."

